1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,300
 So let's learn base sixteen, otherwise known as hexadecimal.

2
00:00:04,300 --> 00:00:10,920
 So the key to, it'd be nice if we could just use base two for everything, but zeros and ones are easy to understand,

3
00:00:10,920 --> 00:00:19,340
 but when numbers get larger, like characters, for example, or eight bits, it's really hard to represent that all in base two.

4
00:00:19,340 --> 00:00:26,760
 So we tend to see in the real world that most machine language and other things require you to understand hexadecimal.

5
00:00:26,760 --> 00:00:30,260
 So if you take a look at base two, it was easy.

6
00:00:30,260 --> 00:00:35,520
 We had a simple conversion table, and I hope by now some of you have memorized this little table.

7
00:00:35,520 --> 00:00:42,020
 I know I've memorized, I just, you know, when I see seven, I see three ones, when I see six, I see one, one, zero.

8
00:00:42,020 --> 00:00:45,100
 I know this by heart, OK?

9
00:00:45,100 --> 00:00:49,980
 Now, that's cool, we're seeing all numbers that we're familiar with.

10
00:00:49,980 --> 00:00:56,720
 Base sixteen says we are going to represent zero through fifteen with a single digit, right?

11
00:00:56,720 --> 00:01:04,140
 So fifteen is fifteen, but with two digits, and so the whole idea of changing bases is that we have digits.

12
00:01:04,140 --> 00:01:12,760
 So we need to come up with a single digit that represents nine, ten, eleven, twelve, thirteen, fourteen, and fifteen.

13
00:01:12,760 --> 00:01:20,360
 And so I basically said, OK, wouldn't it be cool if we would use emojis for that, because I have trouble remembering hexadecimal.

14
00:01:20,360 --> 00:01:33,560
 So if we imagine that ten, which is kind of zero, eleven, twelve, thirteen, they don't have an emoji for four fingers and then fifteen.

15
00:01:33,560 --> 00:01:37,320
 So I put a shamrock in for fourteen.

16
00:01:37,320 --> 00:01:42,940
 And so the point here is you need a single character to represent it.

17
00:01:42,940 --> 00:01:51,720
 And so I made this up and then I'm like, hey, AI, what emojis would you use to represent ten through fifteen?

18
00:01:51,720 --> 00:01:56,560
 So there is an actual emoji that's ten, but there is no emoji for eleven.

19
00:01:56,560 --> 00:02:04,840
 And so they use the pause emoji and then they used a clock, twelve o'clock, one o'clock, two o'clock and three o'clock.

20
00:02:04,840 --> 00:02:10,440
 And it's not too bad. And American Sign Languages uses one hand.

21
00:02:10,440 --> 00:02:15,480
 I think I think this is eleven or maybe. Yeah, I think this is eleven.

22
00:02:15,480 --> 00:02:18,280
 And so British Sign Language is different.

23
00:02:18,280 --> 00:02:23,480
 The problem is, is we don't get emotion. We don't get motion when we make emojis.

24
00:02:23,480 --> 00:02:33,920
 So we can't really use American Sign Language, even though American Sign Language has way to represent eleven, twelve, thirteen, fourteen and fifteen with kind of a gesture.

25
00:02:33,920 --> 00:02:41,440
 So the problem was, is basically whatever, 1930, 1940, when we started using hexadecimal, we didn't have emojis.

26
00:02:41,440 --> 00:02:45,520
 It was just too early. And so all we had was ASCII characters.

27
00:02:45,520 --> 00:02:52,640
 And so we have repurposed A through F to represent ten through fifteen for base sixteen numbers.

28
00:02:52,640 --> 00:02:56,720
 So A is ten, the first number that is not a single digit.

29
00:02:56,720 --> 00:03:03,680
 Right. And F is fifteen and F is all ones for four ones is one, one, one, one, one.

30
00:03:03,680 --> 00:03:12,680
 Is F. OK, so we just used A through F. It's a little weird because there's the letter A and then there is the hexadecimal digit A.

31
00:03:12,680 --> 00:03:16,480
 But you have to kind of get used to it and say, oh, we're in a context of a number here.

32
00:03:16,480 --> 00:03:29,320
 So so that means ten. A means ten. So if we look at the conversion between base sixteen and base ten and I've got my little cheat sheet here of ten through fifteen because zero through nine is pretty easy.

33
00:03:29,320 --> 00:03:37,640
 Again, base ten says that each column is a power of ten. So the far right column is ten to the zero, which is the ones column.

34
00:03:37,640 --> 00:03:40,800
 The middle column is ten to the one, which is the tens column.

35
00:03:40,800 --> 00:03:44,360
 And then the third column is ten squared, which is the hundreds column.

36
00:03:44,360 --> 00:03:54,520
 And so one hundred and twenty three is one times one hundred, two times ten plus three times one, which is one twenty three base ten, which of course it is.

37
00:03:54,520 --> 00:04:00,400
 In base sixteen now, we have more digits to work with. So we have seven be base sixteen.

38
00:04:00,400 --> 00:04:05,800
 Well, the far right is sixteen to the zero or one.

39
00:04:05,800 --> 00:04:10,000
 And then the second digit is sixteen to the first power.

40
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:19,760
 So the result is seven times sixteen plus eleven times one, which is one hundred and twelve plus eleven, which is one hundred and twenty three.

41
00:04:19,760 --> 00:04:26,280
 Now, one thing we like about base sixteen is it's easily converted to and from base two.

42
00:04:26,280 --> 00:04:32,720
 And so if you have eight bit numbers, you can represent them with two base sixteen digits.

43
00:04:32,720 --> 00:04:36,160
 And that's what we're going to work with a lot going forward is eight bit numbers.

44
00:04:36,160 --> 00:04:47,120
 So you can take and convert like seven be base sixteen, which is a byte, and you can convert the seven and then you convert the B and that's the base two.

45
00:04:47,120 --> 00:04:58,360
 And so to some degree, hexadecimal is just a more succinct base two where four digits of base two become one digit of base sixteen.

46
00:04:58,360 --> 00:05:09,440
 If we did this on base ten, there wouldn't be this nice lineup because you can make really long hexadecimal numbers and they still line up on every four bit boundary with base two.

47
00:05:09,440 --> 00:05:19,120
 So for now, keep it simple, I tend to have to go through base ten, you know, we have eights column now.

48
00:05:19,120 --> 00:05:24,320
 So the top line is one eight plus one two, which is ten eight plus two is ten.

49
00:05:24,320 --> 00:05:32,880
 And that is a base sixteen eight, which is one zero zero zero is eight base ten and eight base sixteen.

50
00:05:32,880 --> 00:05:41,320
 So all the numbers zero through nine are easy. And then all ones one one one one is eight plus four plus two plus one, which is fifteen.

51
00:05:41,320 --> 00:05:49,880
 And that's F and base sixteen. So I've told you that I'm pretty much a whiz at base eight, which is three base two digits.

52
00:05:49,880 --> 00:05:57,880
 I can kind of do that in my sleep. I am not very good at base sixteen. Hopefully you'll be better at it or maybe not.

53
00:05:57,880 --> 00:06:03,680
 So this is my this is how I do base sixteen in my head. And it's not pretty.

54
00:06:03,680 --> 00:06:09,440
 So F is easy because that's fifteen. That's the largest base sixteen digit.

55
00:06:09,440 --> 00:06:15,280
 And it's all ones. Right. That's cool. It's base sixteen. F is one less. It's all ones.

56
00:06:15,280 --> 00:06:19,000
 If you add one to it, it's it turns into the sixteen column.

57
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:26,000
 So an E I can do E because I just take the all the digits and I take off the one bit. Right.

58
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:32,240
 So that's like fourteen. I can get that. A is easy because it's like nine.

59
00:06:32,240 --> 00:06:35,560
 What's after nine? Oh, it's A. And so I can do that.

60
00:06:35,560 --> 00:06:42,440
 So I understand that's ten and B is eleven and is like it's kind of like one beyond A.

61
00:06:42,440 --> 00:06:47,760
 And so I can see what B is. I have problems with C and D. Right.

62
00:06:47,760 --> 00:06:54,360
 I mean, I eventually have to slow down and use my brain and go A ten B eleven C twelve.

63
00:06:54,360 --> 00:06:57,320
 And then I have to convert to base two, which is one one zero.

64
00:06:57,320 --> 00:07:00,160
 And then I'm like, oh, that's A plus four. Oh, yeah. Twelve. Yeah.

65
00:07:00,160 --> 00:07:03,560
 There you go. And D just makes me crazy. Right.

66
00:07:03,560 --> 00:07:09,280
 I sooner or later, sometimes with D, I'm like, oh, what is it?

67
00:07:09,280 --> 00:07:16,280
 And then I have to write it down. So for a good time, you can go ahead and ask A.I.

68
00:07:16,280 --> 00:07:20,960
 What is a good way to do hex to base two conversions in your head?

69
00:07:20,960 --> 00:07:24,440
 I did that and it was really complex. So no.

70
00:07:24,440 --> 00:07:27,040
 So maybe I'm OK by being confused about this.

71
00:07:27,040 --> 00:07:33,600
 So just make yourself a little cheat sheet whenever you have to do hex or just get used to it or look at a table.

72
00:07:33,600 --> 00:07:40,280
 A lot of what we're going to do is represent characters and characters are asking characters are eight bits

73
00:07:40,280 --> 00:07:44,800
 and can really nicely and densely be represented by two hex digits.

74
00:07:44,800 --> 00:07:52,320
 We call these half bytes nibbles, not that it matters much, but this ASCII chart shows the decimal,

75
00:07:52,320 --> 00:07:57,040
 the hex octal, which we tend not to use, and then the binary.

76
00:07:57,040 --> 00:08:00,680
 So if you look at 42, it's kind of small on the screen.

77
00:08:00,680 --> 00:08:08,120
 But you see that it's 42 decimal and zero X to a hexadecimal, which is asterisk.

78
00:08:08,120 --> 00:08:12,960
 And so I tend to just look these things up and I don't really convert them

79
00:08:12,960 --> 00:08:17,960
 and just use hex as a way to look things up in things like ASCII tables.

80
00:08:17,960 --> 00:08:26,120
 Now, while we're speaking about ASCII, so ASCII is a historical code set,

81
00:08:26,120 --> 00:08:32,560
 basically, that is very Western and really goes back to Latin, really.

82
00:08:32,560 --> 00:08:39,800
 And because we have eight bit bytes and the West built computers early on,

83
00:08:39,800 --> 00:08:43,880
 we tended to have ASCII character sets were universal across computers.

84
00:08:43,880 --> 00:08:45,480
 But that's not real.

85
00:08:45,480 --> 00:08:51,720
 There's Asian character sets and Indian character sets and Arabic and Persian character sets.

86
00:08:51,720 --> 00:08:54,040
 They're all kind of different.

87
00:08:54,040 --> 00:09:01,440
 And so what happened was in the time where computing became a world wide activity,

88
00:09:01,440 --> 00:09:08,240
 we needed to come up with a way to interchange characters that are way bigger than eight bits.

89
00:09:08,240 --> 00:09:11,440
 And somebody came up with the idea of Unicode.

90
00:09:11,440 --> 00:09:17,920
 And Unicode has all kinds of character sets, you know, Latin and ASCII start.

91
00:09:17,920 --> 00:09:20,400
 And then they just have all kinds of character sets.

92
00:09:20,400 --> 00:09:24,520
 Some of these are Latin characters with like umlauts and all things like that.

93
00:09:24,520 --> 00:09:28,200
 And some of them are like Asian characters that are pictograms.

94
00:09:28,200 --> 00:09:31,360
 Now, recently emojis are in Unicode as well.

95
00:09:31,360 --> 00:09:36,200
 And so some of the emojis that I've showed you are actually have a Unicode code.

96
00:09:36,200 --> 00:09:40,400
 Unicode represents things by 32 bits.

97
00:09:40,400 --> 00:09:45,880
 That's pretty large given that eight bits is how ASCII is represented and Unicode is 32 bits.

98
00:09:45,880 --> 00:09:51,600
 But the idea is, is there's a lot of characters sets around this universe.

99
00:09:51,600 --> 00:09:54,000
 Now, we're not inventing too many more.

100
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:56,760
 And they did things like added emojis to Unicode.

101
00:09:56,760 --> 00:10:01,560
 But basically, 32 bits is like in the billions of possible characters.

102
00:10:01,560 --> 00:10:03,480
 So I think we're probably okay.

103
00:10:03,480 --> 00:10:09,840
 The problem is, is as we move between computers or store data on hard drives,

104
00:10:09,840 --> 00:10:13,000
 we don't really want every character to take up 32 bits.

105
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:17,960
 So for example, Python 3 internally represents strings as Unicode,

106
00:10:17,960 --> 00:10:20,360
 which means they're pretty large.

107
00:10:20,360 --> 00:10:25,320
 Okay, but then before we stick them on a hard drive or send them across a network,

108
00:10:25,320 --> 00:10:34,880
 we condense them and there are ways to compress these 32 bit Unicodes into shorter.

109
00:10:34,880 --> 00:10:38,120
 So one is UTF 32, which is four byte stuff.

110
00:10:38,120 --> 00:10:38,960
 That's the long one.

111
00:10:38,960 --> 00:10:40,200
 It's fixed length.

112
00:10:40,200 --> 00:10:43,760
 And it just says, we'll take that whole Unicode and send it along.

113
00:10:43,760 --> 00:10:46,000
 UTF 16 is fixed length.

114
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:47,160
 It's two bytes.

115
00:10:47,160 --> 00:10:52,760
 It's a lot denser and there's a mapping.

116
00:10:52,760 --> 00:10:56,920
 But the most successful one of these is a thing called UTF-8,

117
00:10:56,920 --> 00:11:02,680
 which might not be intuitive, but basically UTF-8 is one to four bytes.

118
00:11:02,680 --> 00:11:08,880
 And it is for most ASCII, UTF-8 and ASCII are the same things.

119
00:11:08,880 --> 00:11:11,920
 And then there's these little extension codes.

120
00:11:11,920 --> 00:11:15,080
 I mean, this is a 16-bit code or a 32-bit code.

121
00:11:15,080 --> 00:11:19,840
 And so you can represent all of Unicode with UTF-8.

122
00:11:19,840 --> 00:11:23,440
 Sometimes you're sending one byte if it's ASCII, sometimes two,

123
00:11:23,440 --> 00:11:26,360
 three, and even four bytes are being sent across.

124
00:11:26,360 --> 00:11:32,920
 And so UTF-8 is pretty much the practice for encoding data to be exchanged across systems.

125
00:11:32,920 --> 00:11:40,000
 So I got to have a graph here that sort of shows that in 2008, there was choices to be made.

126
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:44,320
 But since then, everything is pretty much UTF-8.

127
00:11:44,320 --> 00:11:52,240
 And so we're at the point now where systems that are reading and writing data to disk or the network only pretty much use UTF-8.

128
00:11:52,240 --> 00:11:54,760
 And it happens to be ASCII, that works OK.

129
00:11:54,760 --> 00:12:01,360
 But what we're doing is we're working on a computer from the 1970s, which is the 6502 computer.

130
00:12:01,360 --> 00:12:05,280
 And so we're going to just accept that it's ASCII for now.

131
00:12:05,280 --> 00:12:12,920
 But real computers tend to work in UTF-8 and can convert from ASCII or Unicode to UTF-8 quite nicely.

132
00:12:14,320 --> 00:12:24,320
 [MUSIC]

